Most booksellers seem to presume that Champel is the engraver. "Mente libera" was the motto of the French bibliophile Eugène Paillet (1829-1901), but his bookplate shows an owl perched on a bookcase, so this probably isn't his.

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: Bookplate of Gaspard Ernest Stroehlin (1844-1907) [authority file has "Ernest Stroehlin" from his publications], a Swiss minister and professor (specializing in church history) at the University of Geneva. "Mente libera" was his motto; "Champel" appears to be an allusion to Champel, Switzerland, where the reformer Michael Servetus was burned at the stake in 1553. The building in the background is probably St. Pierre Cathedral in Geneva, where Calvin famously preached. Hans Asper, whose name appears on this binding, bound at least one other of Stroehlin's books; cf. I. Krekler, Stammbücher bis 1625 (Wiesbaden: Harassowitz, 1999), p. 6 (nr. 2).

From Dunn's obituary:
On Tuesday of last week there died suddenly from pneumonia, at the age of forty-seven, a man whose remarkable gifts and attainments deserve more than the few paragraphs of record that have appeared in the public press. Mr. George Dunn, of Woolley Hall, near Maidenhead, was a member of a well-known Northumbrian Catholic family. He was educated at Beaumont College, Windsor, and at Stonyhurst, and was afterwards called to the Bar, though he never practised as a barrister. Inheriting from his father, the late George Dunn, of Bath House, Newcastle, large estates both in Northumberland and Berkshire, together with sufficient revenues, he was able to indulge the tastes of a scholar and collector of early printed books, mediaeval bindings, manuscripts, old silver, and old clocks, as well as those of a sportsman and keen angler, an astronomer and a student of forestry. Of none of these things was he content to have a superficial knowledge. Indeed, it may be said that he handled nothing without mastering it completely ... With these and other interests and pursuits George Dunn lived a tranquil and sequestered life, unmarried and alone in a large house, where he occasionally entertained one or other of the small band of intimates to whom he was devoted and by whom he was beloved. Neatly dressed, shy, spare, and rather below the middle height, he might sometimes be seen entering the British Museum or the Bodleian Library, or quietly turning over the book-treasures in the London sale rooms. But he never attended meetings or went into society, or gave the smallest encouragement to mere acquaintances. He was a Conservative in politics, a model landlord, and a loyal son of the Catholic Church.
-- "Mr. George Dunn," The Times (11 March 1912), p. 11, issue 39843, col C.

comment.text: It seems that attributing the binder's initials "H I" to a dead Henry Jacobi is not unusual. The Morgan Library has a 1544 edition of Psalms (London : Berthelet) with the same attribution. What is going on? Was it typical for a binder to use another binder's initials or was it simply used as a proprietary mark indicating the stationer/printing company but not the individual binder? Is this not the monogram of Henry Jacobi? There was another binder with the initials H.A. but since he was Jacobi's contemporary(?) it doesn't really answer the question about the date of the binding. It seems that at least one of the stamps (upper board) with the Tudor Rose and arms the City of London and arms of Henry VIII may have been authorized for use by Stationers' Company so maybe it's just a simple case of a reused stamp? See the pic of the upper board and comment referring to Davenport's work "English heraldic book-stamps"(p. 375-376): catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001166193 Another complication is that this binding does not appear to have the pomegranate symbol of Catherine of Aragon. The pomegranate began to disappear on bindings with Henry's coat of arms some time in the mid 1520's(?) after he had begun the long process of divorcing Catherine. Although the divorce was not officially granted until 1533, Henry had long before mentally opted out of his marriage to Catherine and already initiated divorce proceedings. If the binding had been created after the book was printed in 1528 then it seem likely to have the pomegranate omitted. Of course the upper and lower stamps do not have necessarily have to be used together so the pomegranate issue may not have any significance if the front and back stamps could be mixed and matched. For examples and a discussion of binders' initials see Weale's "Bookbindings and Rubbings of Bindings in the National Art Museum" p. xxxv-xxxvi and p. 119-120 books.google.com/books?id=Z15JAAAAYAAJ&pg=PR35&lp... See also Duff's "Early printed books" (p. 143, 156 and 193) Duff's "Early printed books" books.google.com/books/about/Early_Printed_Books.html?id=... and "A guide to the exhibition in the King's Library illustrating the history of printing, music-printing and bookbinding (1901)" archive.org/details/guidetoexhibitio00britiala

In 1597 he published with Thomas Creede a translation of Cleitophon and Leucippe from the Greek of Achilles Tatius, with a dedication to the Earl of Southampton. In 1602 he issued a corrected copy, printed at Antwerp, of Christopher Saxton's map of the county of Leicester. The Description of Leicestershire was begun by 1597. It appeared in 1622, dedicated to George Villiers, Marquess of Buckingham. He then spent years in making large additions and corrections for a new edition. In the summer of 1638 a copy of the intended second edition was sent to London for press. After Burton's death his son Cassibelan presented, with several of his father's manuscripts, to Walter Chetwynd, a copy of the ‘Description’ containing large manuscript additions by the author. In 1798 Shaw discovered this copy at Ingestree, and it was utilised by John Nichols in the third and fourth volumes of his ‘Leicestershire.’ In 1777 there was published by subscription a folio edition which claimed to be ‘enlarged and corrected’; the information contained in the ‘Description’ was incorporated in Nichols's ‘Leicestershire.’ William Dugdale in his ‘Autobiography’ acknowledges the assistance which he had received from Burton. In 1612 Thomas Purefoy of Barwell in Warwickshire bequeathed at his death to Burton the original manuscript of John Leland's ‘Collectanea.’ Anthony Wood says Burton needlessly expanded this work; but Thomas Hearne, in the preface to his edition of the ‘Collectanea,’ denies that. In 1631 Burton caused part of Leland's ‘Itinerary’ to be transcribed, and in the following year he gave five quarto volumes of Leland's autograph manuscripts to the Bodleian Library. Among the manuscripts that he left were: ‘Antiquitates de Lindley,’ which was afterwards in the possession of Samuel Lysons, who lent it to Nichols; ‘Antiquitates de Dadlington Manerio, com. Leic.,’ which in Nichols's time belonged to Nicholas Hurst of Hinckley; Collections towards a history of Thedingworth. About 1735 Francis Peck announced his intention of writing Burton's life, but did not do so.

comment.text: Actually the shelf-mark of Charles de Rohan, prince de Soubise (1715-1787). De Thou’s library was acquired in 1679 by Jean-Jacques Charron, marquis de Ménars (1643-1718), who sold its printed books to Cardinal Armand Gaston de Rohan, bishop of Strasbourg (1674–1749) in 1706. His nephew, Charles de Rohan, inherited them upon his death and they remained in the de Rohan-Soubise family until 1789, when the collection was sold off. Cf. H.P. du Bois, Four Private Libraries of New York (New York: Du Prat & Co., 1892), p. 48; J. Guigard, Armorial du bibliophile, pt. 2 (Paris: Bachelin-Deflorenne, 1871), p. 146-147. Established heading: Soubise, Charles de Rohan, prince de, 1715-1787
